Testing Zoom in the Browser

01
On this page
  1. 📝 Exercise: Identify Behavior when Zooming
  2. Zoom Behavior on the Home & About Pages
    1. Home Page
    2. About Page
  3. Content Should Reflow

The easiest way to test how our page reacts at different zoom levels is in the browser. With browser zoom, the viewport size (or screen width) shrinks and content should grow in size.

Using the CMD + shortcut on Mac (or CTRL + on Windows), zoom in to at least the 200% level (if not all the way to 500%) to see how the page layout reacts. The - will zoom back out.

Pay attention to how menus, text content, images, and interactive behavior changes as you zoom in and out.

📝 Exercise: Identify Behavior when Zooming

Take a few minutes to zoom in and navigate around the Home & About pages of the CampSpots app.

Which elements of the page act like you'd expect?

What behavior or layout changes need to be made on each page?

Zoom Behavior on the Home & About Pages

These are some observations from zooming in:

Home Page

  • The MegaNav has changed its layout in order to fit. The images that are inside the “Plan Your Trip” section disappear at 300% zoom.
  • There’s a large gap between the navigation menu and the search form.
  • The search form is still landscape format and runs off the side of the screen horizontally.
  • The tents image is pretty large.
  • The “Rest and relaxation” text fits well.
  • The three colorful cards stay in landscape format and scroll off the screen.

About Page

  • The image next to the “About” text in the hero section gets scrolled off the side of the page.
  • The Contact form also scrolls off the side of the page.

Content Should Reflow

Several the components of our Home and About pages force the user to have to scroll horizontally in order to see the content.

This is not ideal and it fails to meet the WCAG Level AA success criterion for Reflow.

Reflow is the name for when content that was side by side at a wider viewport changes to be in a column at smaller widths or sizes.

Referencing WCAG suggests solving reflow issues with CSS media queries (as one technique), which we’ll look at further in the next lesson.
